<h1>Relative Minor</h1>
<p>
  A minor and C major share the same key signature — no sharps, no flats — yet
  they are distinct tonalities. Grigson resolves the ambiguity through the
  <code>key:</code> field in the front matter.
</p>
<p>
  Here the key is declared as <code>Am</code>, so the normaliser treats A as
  the tonic. The <code>E7</code> chord is kept as-is: its G# is the raised
  seventh of A harmonic minor, the characteristic sound that defines the
  dominant in minor-key cadences.
</p>
